"'''Strawberry Bubblegum'''" is a song recorded by American singer-songwriter [[Justin Timberlake]] for his third [[studio album]], ''[[The 20/20 Experience]]'' (2013). It was written and produced by Timberlake, [[Timbaland|Timothy "Timbaland" Mosley]] and [[Jerome "J-Roc" Harmon]], with additional writing from James Fauntleroy. "Strawberry Bubblegum" is a mid-tempo [[Pop music|pop]], [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] and [[Soul music|soul]] song with elements of [[Electronic dance music|EDM]] and [[ambient music|ambient]]. Its music structure received comparison to the works of musicians such as [[Barry White]], [[Prince (musician)|Prince]] and [[Stevie Wonder]].

[[Music journalism|Music critics]] were divided on "Strawberry Bubblegum"; the song's production was generally praised, but the lyrics were criticized as being [[clich<U+00E9>]]. Despite the mixed reactions from reviewers, the song debuted at number 22 on the [[Gaon Chart|singles chart]] in South Korea, upon the release of ''The 20/20 Experience''. It also peaked at number 34 and 38 on the [[UK R&B Chart|UK R&B Singles Chart]] and US [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] chart respectively. Timberlake performed "Strawberry Bubblegum" for the first time on ''[[Late Night with Jimmy Fallon]]'' on March 15, 2013.

== Writing and production ==

"Strawberry Bubblegum" was written by Timberlake, [[Timbaland|Timothy "Timbaland" Mosley]], [[Jerome "J-Roc" Harmon]], and James Fauntleroy,<ref name="Album Credits"/> with production by Timbaland, Timberlake and Harmon.<ref name="Album Credits"/> Timberlake arranged and produced his vocals, which were recorded at Larabee Studios in North Hollywood, California.<ref name="Album Credits"/> Harmon provided keyboards for the song, while Elliot Ives played the guitar.<ref name="Album Credits"/> The track was engineered by Chris Godbey, with assistance from Alejandro Baima,<ref name="Album Credits"/> and mixed by Jimmy Douglass, Godbey and Timberlake at Larabee Studios.<ref name="Album Credits"/>

== Composition and lyrical interpretation ==

{{Listen|pos=right|filename=Strawberry Bubblegum.ogg|title="Strawberry Bubblegum"|description=A 30-second sample of "Strawberry Bubblegum", a [[pop music|pop]] and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] song with a combination of slick grooves and [[psychedelic soul]]. It features [[Electronic music|electronic]] blips, [[String instrument|string]] movements, and upbeat percussion breaks.}}

"Strawberry Bubblegum" is characterized as a [[Pop music|pop]] song by [[HitFix]]'s Melinda Newman,<ref name=HitFix>{{cite web|last=Newman |first=Melinda |url=http://www.hitfix.com/news/justin-timberlakes-the-20-20-experience-album-review |title=Justin Timberlakes The 20/20 Experience: Album Review |publisher=[[Hitfix]] |date=March 15, 2013 |accessdate=March 18, 2013}}</ref> an [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] song by ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' magazine's Jason Lipshutz,<ref name=Billboard>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/review/1551360/justin-timberlake-the-2020-experience-track-by-track-review |title=Justin Timberlake, 'The 20/20 Experience': Track-by-Track Review |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |date=March 12, 2013 |accessdate=March 18, 2013}}</ref> and a combination of slick grooves and [[psychedelic soul]] by Arwa Haider of ''[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]''.<ref name="metro">{{cite web|last=Haider |first=Arwa |url=http://metro.co.uk/2013/03/15/justin-timberlake-gets-beyonce-and-jay-z-in-on-the-2020-experience-3542473 |title=Album review: Justin Timberlake's 20/20 Experience hits the spot |publisher=Metro.co.uk |date=March 15, 2012 |accessdate=March 18, 2013}}</ref> Jean Bentley of [[Hollywood.com]] found the song influenced by [[electro (music)|electro]],<ref name=Hollywood>{{cite web|last=Bentley |first=Jean |url=http://www.hollywood.com/news/celebrities/55003811/justin-timberlake-the-20-20-experience-streaming-review |title=Justin Timberlake's 'The 20/20 Experience' is Streaming Online Right Now! An Early Review &#124; Celebrity News |publisher=Hollywood.com |date=March 11, 2013 |accessdate=March 18, 2013}}</ref> while [[Pitchfork Media]]'s Ryan Dombal said that it evokes music by [[Barry White]], [[Sly Stone]], and [[Drake (entertainer)|Drake]]'s "[[ambient music|ambient]] R&B" style.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/17736-justin-timberlake-the-2020-experience |title=Justin Timberlake: The 20/20 Experience |publisher=Pitchfork |date=March 19, 2013 |accessdate=March 29, 2013}}</ref> According to Mikael Wood of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', the song transitions from a stark electro song to an amiable keyboard [[vamp (music)|vamp]] comparable to [[Stevie Wonder]]'s 1973 song "[[You Are the Sunshine of My Life]]".<ref name="LA Times">{{cite news|last=Wood|first=Mikael|date=March 14, 2013|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/posts/la-et-ms-album-review-justin-timberlake-the-20-20-experience-20130314,0,1032937.story|title=Album review: Justin Timberlake's 'The 20/20 Experience'|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=March 15, 2013|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6FBDlyH6c|archivedate=March 17, 2013|deadurl=no}}</ref> The song features [[Electronic music|electronic]] blips, [[String instrument|string]] movements, and upbeat percussion breaks.<ref name=Billboard/> Mesfin Fekadu of ''[[Times Colonist]]'' wrote that the song is "smooth, airy and full of [[Sexual innuendo|sexual innuendoes]], and it transitions into something that's heaven-like."<ref name="timescolonist">{{cite news|url=http://www.timescolonist.com/entertainment/music/review-justin-timberlake-s-20-20-experience-is-near-perfect-echoes-futuresex-lovesounds-1.93442|title=Review: Justin Timberlake's '20/20 Experience' is near perfect, echoes 'FutureSex/LoveSounds'|work=[[Times Colonist]]|publisher= TC Publication Limited Partnership ([[Glacier Media]])|last=Fekadu|first=Mesfin|last=Fekadu|date=March 18, 2013|accessdate=March 27, 2013}}</ref> Timberlake sings in a [[falsetto]] voice and refers to a mature woman as his strawberry bubblegum in the song's lyrics.<ref name="VH1">{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/music/tuner/2013-03-20/justin-timberlakes-the-2020-experience-is-from-the-future/|title=Justin Timberlake's The 20/20 Experience is from the future|publisher=[[VH1]]. [[Viacom]]|last=Viera|first=Bene|date=March 20, 2013|accessdate=March 27, 2013}}</ref> Joey Guerra of ''[[The Houston Chronicle]]'' remarked that the eccentric song recalls the work of [[Prince (musician)|Prince]].<ref name=Chron>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/life/article/Not-a-drop-of-hindsight-on-forward-looking-20-20-4358347.php |title=Not a drop of hindsight on forward-looking '20/20'&nbsp;<U+2013> Houston Chronicle |publisher=Chron.com |date=March 15, 2013 |accessdate=March 18, 2013}}</ref> Helen Brown of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' attributed the song's relaxing style to how it samples [[Barry White]],<ref name=Telegraph>{{cite news|last=Brown|first=Helen|date=March 15, 2013|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/cdreviews/9931132/Justin-Timberlake-The-2020-Experience-album-review.html|title=Justin Timberlake, The 20/20 Experience, album review|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|location=London|accessdate=March 15, 2013|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6FBEDGF5b|archivedate=March 17, 2013|deadurl=no}}</ref> while Lauren Martin of ''[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]]'' found the song to be in the style of [[Frank Ocean]].<ref name="FACTMAG">{{cite web|url=http://www.factmag.com/2013/03/18/justin-timberlake-the-2020-experience-fact-review/|title=Justin Timberlake&nbsp;<U+2013> The 20/20 Experience|publisher=[[Fact (magazine)|Fact]]|last=Martin|first=Lauren|date=March 18, 2013|accessdate=March 28, 2013}}</ref>

"Strawberry Bubblegum" begins with the sound of a [[stylus]] dropping on a [[vinyl record]], which Gregory Hicks of ''[[The Michigan Daily]]'' felt evoked a characteristic sound from [[Christina Aguilera]]'s 2006 album ''[[Back to Basics (Christina Aguilera album)|Back to Basics]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.michigandaily.com/arts/03justin-timberlake-%E2%80%93-2020-experience18 |title=Timberlake introduces a seductive, new generation of R&B for 'The 20/20 Experience' |publisher=The Michigan Daily |date=March 18, 2013 |accessdate=March 29, 2013}}</ref> The line "Hey, pretty lady" is declared by a deep voice, and Timberlake sings "This goes out to you!".<ref name="ABC NEWS"/> [[ABC News]] reporter Allan Raible wrote that "such a move seems engineered to make gullible teen girls in the audience scream".<ref name="ABC NEWS">{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/entertainment/2013/03/review-justin-timberlakes-the-2020-experience/|title=Review: Justin Timberlake's 'The 20/20 Experience'|publisher=[[ABC News]]. [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]|last=Rabile|first=Allan|date=March 23, 2013|accessdate=March 27, 2013}}</ref> The lyrics feature daft double-entendres and are complemented by spoken-word background vocals.<ref name="MusicOMH"/> [[MusicOMH]]'s David Meller wrote that the song's transition into "<U+2019>70s funk-cum-porno keyboards" is likable, but may seem ridiculous to many listeners.<ref name="MusicOMH">{{cite web|url=http://www.musicomh.com/reviews/albums/justin-timberlake-the-2020-experience|title=Justin Timberlake&nbsp;<U+2013> The 20/20 Experience|publisher=[[MusicOMH]]|last=Meller|first=David|date=March 15, 2013|accessdate=March 17, 2013}}</ref> The string loops and the record scratches on the song complete "the faux-vintage" vibe of "Strawberry Bubblegum". Raible concluded that it attempts to sound like [[Michael Jackson]]'s 2002 song "[[Butterflies (Michael Jackson song)|Butterflies]]" because of its delicate tone.<ref name="ABC NEWS"/> According to Clyde Erwin Barretto of Prefix Mag, "Strawberry Bubblegum" takes its R&B style in a more avant-garde direction, but its second half is more classic-sounding.<ref name="Prefix Mag"/> Craig Manning of the ''[[Western Herald]]'' said that the first half of "Strawberry Bubblegum" draws from Frank Ocean's psychedelic style of R&B, while the outro is more comparable to the music of '[[N Sync]], Timberlake's former group.<ref>{{cite web|author=Required |url=http://www.westernherald.com/arts-and-entertainment/album-review-justin-timberlakes-latest-is-pop-excess-at-its-finest |title=Justin Timberlake<U+2019>s latest is pop excess at its finest |publisher=[[Western Herald]] |date=March 20, 2013 |accessdate=March 29, 2013}}</ref> Jason Lipshutz called the outro "sashaying" and "pleasant".<ref name=Billboard/>

Lyrically, Timberlake assures his love interest that they are "making love like professionals" and declares: "If you<U+2019>ll be my strawberry bubblegum, I<U+2019>ll be your blueberry lollipop".<ref name="dailymail">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2297186/Justin-Timberlake-The-20-20-Experience-review-Justin-strutting-new-beat.html|title=Justin is strutting to a whole new beat: The Tennessee Kid refuses to play safe|work=[[Daily Mail]]|publisher=[[Daily Mail and General Trust]]|last=Thrills|first=Adrian|date=March 21, 2013|accessdate=March 27, 2013}}</ref> In addition, he sings about the girl's many characteristics and sensual qualities,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1703486/justin-timberlake-20-20-experience.jhtml|title=Justin Timberlake's The 20/20 Experience: The Bachelor, The Bride, And The In-Between|publisher=[[MTV News]]. Viacom|last=Montgomery|first=James|date=March 12, 2013|accessdate=March 27, 2013}}</ref> and proclaims that he will love her until they "make it pop".<ref name=HitFix/> ''[[The Boston Globe]]''{{'}}s James Reed wrote that the lyrics are silly, but irresistible,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/ae/music/2013/03/14/justin-timberlake-unfettered-confident-new-album/sUQ21qbAEmntoWnewiPfdI/story.html |title=Justin Timberlake's unfettered, confident new album |newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]]|date=March 14, 2013 |accessdate=March 18, 2013}}</ref> while Sarah Dean of ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' found "Strawberry Bubblegum" as seductive as its title, but according to her, "if you had too much of it you might end up feeling a little sick".<ref name=Huffington>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2013/03/01/justin-timberlake-the-20-20-experience_n_2788429.html |title=Justin Timberlake 'The 20/20 Experience' Review: It's Good to Hear from an Old Friend |publisher=The Huffington Post|last=Dean|first=Sarah |date=March 15, 2013 |accessdate=March 19, 2013}}</ref> Additionally, Timberlake sings lyrics about he has "recipe for a good time".<ref name=Huffington/> Genevieve Koski of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' felt that the lyrics' sense of humor is somewhat similar to "[[Pop (song)|Pop]]" by 'N Sync.<ref>{{cite web|last=Koski |first=Genevieve |url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/justin-timberlake-the-2020-experience,93905 |title=Justin Timberlake: The 20/20 Experience &#124; Music &#124; MusicalWork Review |work=[[The A.V. Club]] |date=March 19, 2013 |accessdate=March 19, 2013}}</ref>

== Critical response ==
Mesfin Fekadu of the ''Times Colonist'' called "Strawberry Bubblegum" an "eight-minute event" and one of the album's standout songs.<ref name="timescolonist"/> Sean Daly of the ''[[Tampa Bay Times]]'' wrote that the song is "best enjoyed on satin sheets".<ref>{{cite web|first=Sean |last=Daly |url=http://www.tampabay.com/things-to-do/music/review-justin-timberlakes-new-the-2020-experience-is-a-smooth-ride/2109695 |title=Review: Justin Timberlake's new 'The 20/20 Experience' is a smooth ride &#124; Things to do in Tampa Bay &#124; Tampa Bay Times |publisher=Tampabay.com |date=March 18, 2013 |accessdate=March 29, 2013}}</ref> Clyde Erwin Barretto of Prefix Mag wrote that "as the name suggests", the song is "as sweet as it sounds".<ref name="Prefix Mag">{{cite web|author=Clyde Erwin Barretto |url=http://www.prefixmag.com/reviews/justin-timberlake/the-2020-experience/73185/ |title=Album Review: Justin Timberlake&nbsp;<U+2013> The 20/20 Experience &#124; Prefix |publisher=Prefixmag.com |date=March 20, 2013 |accessdate=March 29, 2013}}</ref> Kitty Empire of ''[[The Observer]]'' wrote that the "surface silliness" of the song "deepens to a feeling of respect a few plays in, when the penny drops, and everything suddenly makes sense".<ref>{{cite web|first=Kitty |last=Empire |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/2013/mar/17/justin-timberlake-20-experience-review |title=Justin Timberlake: The 20/20 Experience&nbsp;<U+2013> review |publisher=Guardian |date=March 17, 2013 |accessdate=March 29, 2013}}</ref>

Robert Copsey of [[Digital Spy]] wrote that while "Strawberry Bubblegum" is musically "rich and rewarding", the lyrics are "embarrassingly clich<U+00E9>".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.ca/music/albumreviews/a465794/justin-timberlake-the-2020-experience-album-review.html |title=Justin Timberlake: 'The 20/20 Experience'&nbsp;<U+2013> Album review&nbsp;<U+2013> Music Album Review&nbsp;<U+2013> Digital Spy |publisher=Digitalspy.ca |date=March 14, 2013 |accessdate=March 29, 2013}}</ref> According to [[VH1]]'s Ben<U+00E9> Viera, one would expect a clich<U+00E9> such as "Strawberry Bubblegum" to "fall flat".<ref name="VH1"/> He wrote that Timberlake's falsettos "make it almost cute" to hear a "grown man referring to a grown woman as his strawberry bubblegum".<ref name="VH1"/> He concluded that envisioning Timberlake perform on stage at a "small juke joint on Bill Street" is not "far fetched".<ref name="VH1"/> Lauren Martin of ''[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]]'' wrote that "if you<U+2019>re going to release an eight minute song with only two verses and a hook", singing the words "strawberry" and "bubblegum" 34 and 20 times respectively "begins to grate".<ref name="FACTMAG"/> Jed Gottlieb of ''[[The Boston Herald]]'' wrote that "Strawberry Bubblegum" is a "killer vamp" without a "killer change to hook us".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bostonherald.com/entertainment/music/album_reviews/2013/03/justin_timberlake_robs_from_the_past_for_his_new_release |title=Justin Timberlake robs from the past for his new release |publisher=Boston Herald |date=March 17, 2013 |accessdate=March 29, 2013}}</ref>

== Live performances ==
Timberlake performed "Strawberry Bubblegum" for the first time on ''[[Late Night with Jimmy Fallon]]'' on March 15, 2013.<ref name="Buzzworthy live">{{cite web|url=http://buzzworthy.mtv.com/2013/03/15/justin-timberlake-strawberry-bubblegum-on-late-night-jimmy-fallon-video |title=Watch Justin Timberlake Perform 'Strawberry Bubblegum' On 'Late Night With Jimmy Fallon' (VIDEO) |publisher=Buzzworthy.mtv.com |date=March 15, 2013 |accessdate=March 29, 2013}}</ref> Wearing varsity baseball-style jackets, Timberlake and his backup singers "shook and finger-snapped" through the song, according to Rachel Brodsky of [[MTV Buzzworthy]].<ref name="Buzzworthy live"/> "Building upon the performance's sports theme", additional backup dancers later joined them onstage in full baseball uniforms.<ref name="Buzzworthy live"/> Brodsky suggested that the choice of wearing baseball hats and striped pants could "have something to do with baseball players and their penchant for chewing [bubble]gum".<ref name="Buzzworthy live"/>

